                <td class="p-3">"I need to seem like a fit for everything."</td>
                <td class="p-3">"I'll be honest about what I haven't done. I'd rather a fit than a sale."</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]">
                <td class="p-3">"I'll talk fast to fit it all in."</td>
                <td class="p-3">"I'll talk slowly. My time costs $150K a year, what I say has to land."</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Three things to do because you're a vendor, not a candidate</h4>
          <ol class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted list-decimal list-inside">
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Diagnose before you prescribe.</span> Ask 1-2 questions about the situation before you launch into your answer.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Quote your evidence.</span> Specific numbers, specific roles, specific outcomes. Generic statements are how candidates lose.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">Name the gap.</span> When you don't have something, say so, then offer the closest analogue. Honesty in a sales call builds trust faster than coverage.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

