    <section id="objections" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 8B</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-4">Objections &amp; Counters</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-6">Every realistic concern Kevin (or a future panel) might have about your fit, with what they're actually worried about underneath, the reframe, the story to deploy, and the exact opener. Read once. Don't memorize. The point of having an answer ready is so you can <span class="italic">slow down</span> when you hear the question.</p>

        <div class="bg-secondary/5 border border-secondary/15 rounded-xl p-5 mb-8">
          <p class="text-sm text-primary leading-relaxed"><span class="font-semibold">Universal rule:</span> <span class="text-text-muted">when an objection lands, do two things before you answer. (1) <span class="font-medium">Acknowledge</span> ("That's a fair thing to ask.") (2) <span class="font-medium">Diagnose</span> with a sentence that surfaces the underlying concern. Then answer. Most candidates skip step 1 and step 2 and rush the answer; that's how you "lose" objections you actually had the right answer to.</span></p>
